  abstract: >-
    Knowledge bases in logic programming grow through fact accumulation
    but do not learn. We present DreamLog, a system that compresses its
    knowledge base through wake-sleep cycles, discovering rules that
    generalize to unseen entities, and a test protocol that makes the
    compression-versus-memorization distinction auditable by pairing fact
    bases over invented vocabulary with a raw-LLM baseline on identical
    inputs. On a synthetic crafting domain with invented terms unknown to
    the LLM, symbolic compression alone recovers 53% of held-out
    generalizations and the full pipeline 63%, while a raw LLM recovers 0%;
    recursive transitive closures are recovered at 100% even over invented
    vocabulary. On a canonical family tree the full pipeline reaches 80%
    recall at 100% precision. Refining the acceptance criterion from clause
    count to a rename-invariant, parameter-free bits-based description
    length makes it structure-sensitive, and across twenty-two synthetic
    domains the degree of compression predicts held-out recovery (Pearson
    r=0.52, n=22, p=0.014). Compared against three inductive-logic-programming
    paradigms (Popper, Metagol, ILASP), DreamLog sits at the low-supervision
    end of a prior-knowledge spectrum. These results are consistent with the
    Solomonoff thesis that shorter programs generalize better.
